         <h3>We Made It To The Grand Canyon!</h3>
        <p>What makes the Grand Canyon so Grand? It's not the deepest Canyon, nor the longest, nor the widest. So why do they consider it the Grand Canyon? It's because of the many visible layers of erosion that have occurred over millions of
            years. The first thing that stood out to me is that how an area that's so flat on its top could erode so beautifully and marvelously. Another thing that stood out is that it has many twists and turns, and at a length of 277 miles
            long, we hardly saw any of it. It's incredible how much of the Grand Canyon actually exists. Again, its not the longest nor deepest, but the colors make it truly unique.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>The Grand Canyon is 277 miles long.</li>
            <li>The Grand Canyon is 18 miles wide (at its largest width)</li>
            <li>The Grand Canyon has a depth of over 6,000 feet.</li>
            <li>The largest canyon in the world (by most measures) is the Yarlung Tsangpo Grand Canyon in Tibet, China, with a length of 314 miles, with depths reaching 19,000 feet.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The first place we stopped at to view the Grand Canyon was Hopi Point. The Hopi are a Native American tribe in the area. They consider the Grand Canyon to be a holy place. Looking at all the viewpoints was amazing. Holding on the railings
            was even more necessary as looking down in the Canyon would make one want to run away as far as one can. Especially being a Male in the 25-35 age range; the leading category of people who die in the Grand Canyon. I was exactly
            halfway in the range. Did I need a leash? No, like the mules that travel into the Grand Canyon with people riding them, they will instinctively avoid danger. Let the reckless people be more reckless, I'm no longer in my 20s. It
            was also here that I saw the first of many elk in the Grand Canyon. Not as big as the one Elk I saw at Yellowstone, but still impressive.</p>
        <p>The next stop was Mohave Point, another grand point of the Grand Canyon. Just seeing the Colorado River so far down look like a small sliver compared to the enormous size of the Grand Canyon puts everything in perspective. Imagine
            being down at the Colorado River looking up at the Grand Canyon. Now that would be an experience! Unfortunately, that's a two day trip in itself, so I'll happily stay at the top of the Grand Canyon.</p>
         <h3>Facts About the Colorado River</h3>
        <p>The Colorado River River is 1,450 miles, beginning in the Rocky Mountains in Colorado, and ending in the Gulf of California in Baja, Mexico.</p>
        <p>The Colorado River runs through Colorado, Utah, Arizona, Nevada, California, as well as Mexico states Baja and Sonora.</p>
        <p>It generally flows southwest, before hitting Lake Mead in Nevada and flowing south. It is the basis of Arizona's western border with Nevada and California</p>
        <p>Eleven National Parks (including the Grand Canyon) are found in the watershed of the Colorado River, including Arches, Bryce Canyon, Zion and Rocky Mountain National Parks, among others.</p>
