         <h3>Grand Canyon National Park</h3>
        <p>Grand Canyon National Park covers 1,217,262 acres of land, stretch from the Nevada border to the Utah border.</p>
        <p>The North Rim also has places to visit, though it is less visited and more remote than the South Rim. Only one road, AZ 87 reaches the North Rim.</p>
        <p>Though the South Rim is just across the Grand Canyon from the North Rim, there is no direct crossing of the canyon. Therefore, it would take 4 hours to drive from the South Rim entrance to the North Rim entrance.</p>
        <p>The Grand Canyon Skywalk, owned by the Hualapai Tribe, sits on the western edge of the Grand Canyon, is 4 hours from Grand Canyon Village (but 2 hours from Las Vegas).</p>
        <p>To walk down and back up the Grand Canyon typically takes two days to complete. It is discouraged by the Park to attempt the trek in one day due to risk of heat exhaustion, distance, steep hills, among other things.</p>
        <p>Only two bridges cross the Grand Canyon, the Navajo Bridge near the border with Utah, and the Mike O'Callaghan-Pat Tillman Memorial Bridge, near the Hoover Dam</p>
         <h3>Hopi</h3>
        <p>The Hopi Tribe is one of the more famous tribes in the Grand Canyon Area, along with the Navajo. Their name is a shortened word meaning "Peaceful People". They consider the Grand Canyon to be a holy place (along with most of the land
            they live on). Today they live in Hopi Reservation, in Northeastern Arizona, surrounded by the much larger Navajo Nation.</p>
        <p>Hopi's are famous for their Pueblo homes and Kachina dolls, which came from the Ancestral Pueblo people from which they descended from. An example of the a pueblo is the Hopi House at the Grand Canyon National Park, originally built
            for Native American tribes to sell arts and crafts.</p>
        <p>As of 2012, there are 18,000 members of the Hopi Reservation, which was created in 1882 by President Chester A Arthur. They live to the east of the Grand Canyon. Despite being surrounded by the Navajo Reservation, the only part of
            Arizona to observe Daylight Savings Time, the Hopi Reservation, like the rest of Arizona, does not observe Daylight Savings Time.</p>
         <h3>Mohave</h3>
        <p>The Mohave (or Mojave) Tribe are indigenous to the Colorado River. They currently live on Fort Mojave Indian Reservation, living on the Colorado River, in Arizona, California and Nevada. They also maintain the Colorado River Indian
            Reservation, in California and Arizona, also along the Colorado River.</p>
        <p>There are about 2,000 members of the Tribe (as of 2007) living on the reservation, which unlike most Indian Reservations, has a significant non-Native American population, as they rent their land out to agricultural based companies.</p>
